{"insight":"Borrowed words must grow in shared life","publicTitle":"When Borrowed Words Can Help","plainSummary":"Shared words help only when they lead us toward honesty, real contact, and correction.","atAGlance":"Borrowed spiritual words can steady a person, but they cannot stand alone. For public teaching, we must know where the words came from and what life formed them. For a lonely person, the first sign is whether the words lead toward honesty, real contact, and correction. Words that isolate, flatter, or excuse harm should be set down.","keyPoints":["Public teaching must honor the life that formed its words.","A warm group can still teach harm.","Keep the saying only if it makes life more honest."],"match":["borrowed words"],"tags":["discernment","teaching","loneliness","community"]}
